{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Artificial Intelligence is the field of building systems that can recognize patterns, make predictions, generate language or images, and choose actions. It matters because AI already helps filter messages, recommend music, detect fraud, assist doctors, guide robots, and speed up creative work. This chapter gives a friendly first look at what AI does, why it feels so powerful, and where people use it in real life.",
    "title": "Artificial Intelligence in Everyday Life"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "AI is not one single machine mind. It is a collection of methods for making computers act in ways that seem intelligent: spotting objects, translating text, answering questions, planning routes, or finding unusual activity in data.",
      "title": "What Artificial Intelligence Really Does"
    },
    {
      "description": "Many AI systems improve by finding patterns in examples. Instead of being told every rule by hand, they compare lots of cases and adjust until their guesses get better. That idea powers tools that recognize speech, sort photos, and predict what someone might click next.",
      "title": "How AI Learns From Patterns"
    },
    {
      "description": "AI often appears in small moments: autocorrect fixing a typo, a bank flagging a suspicious purchase, a phone unlocking with face recognition, or a streaming app suggesting a show. These systems can be useful, but their choices also affect privacy, fairness, and trust.",
      "title": "Where Artificial Intelligence Shows Up Around You"
    },
    {
      "description": "Generative AI can produce text, images, code, music, and designs from prompts. It works less like a search engine and more like a pattern-based creator, combining what it has absorbed into new outputs that still need human judgment.",
      "title": "How Generative AI Creates New Content"
    },
    {
      "description": "People use AI as researchers, software developers, data scientists, product designers, robotics builders, artists, policy analysts, and ethics reviewers. AI projects can include chatbots, medical image tools, recommendation systems, game characters, accessibility apps, and climate data models.",
      "title": "What People Build With Artificial Intelligence"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "A Biologia investiga a vida em muitas escalas: moléculas, células, organismos, ecossistemas e evolução. Ela ajuda a explicar por que respiramos, como doenças se espalham, como alimentos são produzidos, por que espécies mudam ao longo do tempo e como seres vivos dependem uns dos outros. É uma área cheia de perguntas concretas, ideias poderosas e aplicações em saúde, ambiente, tecnologia, agricultura e conservação.",
    "title": "Biologia: a ciência da vida em ação"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "A Biologia observa o que seres vivos fazem: crescem, usam energia, reagem ao ambiente, se reproduzem e carregam informações herdadas. De bactérias a florestas, ela procura padrões que conectam formas de vida muito diferentes.",
      "title": "O que a Biologia estuda nos seres vivos"
    },
    {
      "description": "Todo ser vivo é feito de células, pequenas unidades capazes de realizar tarefas essenciais. Dentro delas acontecem processos como produção de energia, comunicação, reparo e cópia de informações — atividades que sustentam desde uma folha até o corpo humano.",
      "title": "Como as células mantêm a vida funcionando"
    },
    {
      "description": "A evolução mostra como populações mudam ao longo das gerações. Essa ideia explica semelhanças entre espécies, adaptações surpreendentes, resistência de bactérias a antibióticos e a enorme diversidade de vida no planeta.",
      "title": "Por que a evolução organiza a diversidade da vida"
    },
    {
      "description": "A Biologia aparece em vacinas, exames, cultivo de alimentos, saneamento, conservação de espécies, controle de pragas e decisões sobre clima e saúde pública. Muitas escolhas do dia a dia ficam mais claras quando se conhece como os sistemas vivos funcionam.",
      "title": "Como a Biologia aparece na saúde, no alimento e no ambiente"
    },
    {
      "description": "Biólogos podem trabalhar em laboratórios, hospitais, escolas, parques, museus, empresas, fazendas, ONGs e projetos de pesquisa. Eles analisam DNA, monitoram ecossistemas, estudam doenças, cuidam de coleções científicas e ajudam a resolver problemas ligados à vida real.",
      "title": "O que biólogos fazem com conhecimento sobre a vida"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Quantum mechanics is the science of nature at its smallest scales: atoms, electrons, photons, and the rules that make them behave unlike everyday objects. It explains why matter is stable, why light comes in packets, how modern electronics work, and why measuring something can change what can be known about it. This opening chapter frames quantum mechanics as both a practical engine of technology and one of the strangest, most beautiful ways humans describe reality.",
    "title": "Quantum mechanics and the strange rules of the small"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Quantum mechanics studies the behavior of particles and light when ordinary intuition stops working. Instead of tiny billiard balls following neat paths, the quantum world uses probabilities, wave-like behavior, and careful measurement to describe what nature can do.",
      "title": "What quantum mechanics says nature is doing"
    },
    {
      "description": "In quantum mechanics, a single electron can act as if it takes multiple possible paths until a measurement pins down an outcome. This idea is not just weird philosophy; it helps explain real patterns seen in experiments with light, atoms, and matter.",
      "title": "Why quantum particles do not act like tiny planets"
    },
    {
      "description": "Quantum mechanics is behind lasers, MRI scans, solar cells, LEDs, computer chips, atomic clocks, and many sensors. The theory may sound abstract, but it helps engineers and scientists control light, electricity, magnetism, and materials with remarkable precision.",
      "title": "How quantum mechanics powers modern technology"
    },
    {
      "description": "Quantum mechanics raises sharp questions: What can be predicted exactly? What does a measurement do? Why are atoms stable? How can two particles share a connection across distance? These questions make the field useful in physics, chemistry, computing, materials science, and philosophy.",
      "title": "The big questions quantum mechanics asks"
    },
    {
      "description": "People use quantum ideas to design new materials, build quantum computers, improve medical imaging, study stars, secure communication, and model molecules. The field connects researchers, engineers, chemists, programmers, and curious makers working with the deepest rules of matter and information.",
      "title": "What people build with quantum mechanics"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Civil procedure is the rulebook for how civil lawsuits move through court: who can sue where, what each side must share, how judges manage disputes, and when a case truly ends. It matters because these rules shape real fights over contracts, injuries, housing, employment, civil rights, business, and government power. The subject turns courtroom drama into a system of deadlines, documents, strategy, fairness, and public decision-making.",
    "title": "How Civil Procedure Shapes a Lawsuit"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Civil procedure focuses on the path of a civil case, not the underlying wrong itself. It asks questions like: Which court can hear this dispute? How does the defendant get notice? What facts must each side reveal? When can a judge decide a case without a trial? These rules can determine whether a claim is heard at all.",
      "title": "What Civil Procedure Is Really About"
    },
    {
      "description": "A lawsuit is partly a story and partly a sequence of required steps. Complaints, answers, motions, discovery, settlement talks, trials, and appeals each serve a purpose. Civil procedure studies how those steps keep a dispute organized while giving both sides a fair chance to be heard.",
      "title": "How Civil Lawsuits Move Through Court"
    },
    {
      "description": "Courts cannot decide every dispute everywhere. Jurisdiction rules connect lawsuits to places, people, governments, and authority. A business selling online, a car crash across state lines, or a contract signed in one state and broken in another can all raise the question: which court has power here?",
      "title": "Why Jurisdiction Controls Where Civil Cases Happen"
    },
    {
      "description": "Discovery is the part of civil procedure where parties demand documents, answer questions, and gather evidence before trial. It can reveal emails, contracts, medical records, company policies, or witness testimony. Many cases settle after discovery because the facts become clearer and the risks become harder to ignore.",
      "title": "How Discovery Finds the Facts Before Trial"
    },
    {
      "description": "Civil procedure is central to litigation work, but it also matters beyond courtrooms. Lawyers, paralegals, compliance teams, journalists, policy advocates, and business leaders all benefit from knowing how legal claims become formal disputes. Procedure affects negotiation leverage, public accountability, and access to justice.",
      "title": "Where Civil Procedure Shows Up in Legal Work and Society"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Una mirada clara al urbanismo: cómo las calles, viviendas, parques, servicios y reglas dan forma a la vida diaria en una ciudad. Verás por qué una banqueta, una ruta de bus o una plaza pueden cambiar la salud, el trabajo, la seguridad y la convivencia de miles de personas.",
    "title": "Cómo el urbanismo da forma a la vida en la ciudad"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "El urbanismo estudia cómo se organizan los espacios donde vivimos: barrios, avenidas, transporte, vivienda, áreas verdes, comercios y servicios. No trata solo de edificios, sino de cómo las personas se mueven, se encuentran, descansan, trabajan y participan en la ciudad.",
      "title": "Qué estudia el urbanismo en una ciudad"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una calle puede invitar a caminar o empujar a usar auto. Su ancho, sombra, cruces, iluminación, velocidad del tráfico y comercios cercanos influyen en accidentes, ventas, ruido, calor y sensación de seguridad.",
      "title": "Cómo una calle urbana cambia la vida diaria"
    },
    {
      "description": "La ubicación de una parada de transporte, una clínica o una escuela puede ahorrar horas cada semana o volver la vida más difícil. El urbanismo ayuda a ver esas conexiones entre distancia, tiempo, acceso y oportunidades.",
      "title": "Por qué la ubicación importa en urbanismo"
    },
    {
      "description": "Los parques, árboles y cuerpos de agua no son solo decoración. Pueden bajar la temperatura, absorber lluvia, mejorar la salud mental, crear comunidad y dar refugio a la biodiversidad dentro de la ciudad.",
      "title": "Cómo las áreas verdes mejoran la ciudad"
    },
    {
      "description": "El urbanismo aparece en municipios, despachos de diseño, organizaciones vecinales, movilidad, vivienda, medio ambiente, datos urbanos y participación ciudadana. Sus proyectos van desde rediseñar una esquina peligrosa hasta planear barrios más justos y resistentes al clima.",
      "title": "Qué hacen las personas que trabajan en urbanismo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "L’histoire de l’art regarde les œuvres comme des traces vivantes : elles montrent des façons de croire, de gouverner, d’aimer, de protester, de décorer, de raconter et de voir le monde. Des grottes peintes aux musées, des cathédrales aux affiches, elle relie les images aux sociétés qui les ont produites et à celles qui les regardent encore.",
    "title": "L’art comme mémoire visible des sociétés"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Une œuvre n’est pas seulement « belle » ou « célèbre ». L’histoire de l’art s’intéresse à ce qu’elle représente, à sa matière, à son lieu, à son commanditaire, à son public et aux idées qu’elle fait circuler. Un tableau, une statue ou un bâtiment peut devenir une sorte d’enquête sur une époque.",
      "title": "Ce que l’histoire de l’art cherche dans une œuvre"
    },
    {
      "description": "Une même couleur, un geste de la main, une auréole, une ruine ou un fruit peuvent changer de sens selon les périodes et les cultures. L’histoire de l’art aide à lire ces signes sans réduire l’œuvre à un simple message caché.",
      "title": "Comment les images racontent sans parler"
    },
    {
      "description": "Les œuvres naissent souvent dans des réseaux concrets : ateliers, cours royales, églises, marchés, salons, galeries, rues, écrans. Elles peuvent servir à prier, impressionner, vendre, commémorer, critiquer ou transformer un espace public.",
      "title": "Pourquoi les œuvres d’art existent dans la vie sociale"
    },
    {
      "description": "La perspective, le clair-obscur, le collage, la photographie ou l’installation ont changé la manière de représenter le réel. L’histoire de l’art montre comment une invention visuelle peut modifier notre façon de regarder un visage, une ville ou un événement.",
      "title": "Quand une technique change le regard"
    },
    {
      "description": "Conservateurs, médiateurs, restaurateurs, chercheurs, commissaires d’exposition, guides, critiques et créateurs utilisent l’histoire de l’art pour attribuer, préserver, présenter et questionner les œuvres. Elle nourrit aussi des projets dans les musées, le patrimoine, l’édition, le cinéma, le design et les cultures numériques.",
      "title": "Ce que l’histoire de l’art permet de faire"
    }
  ]
}
